Team 7: Spotify Songs Analysis

Team Members: Sarva Praneeth, Lakshmi Sashrika Pathuri, Aravinda Vijayaram Kumar

Introduction

In the expansive realm of music streaming services, delving into the characteristics of songs can offer valuable insights into both user preferences and genre-specific trends. Amid the vast catalog of tracks accessible on platforms like Spotify, the ability to uncover patterns and connections between diverse audio attributes holds the potential to predict song popularity, curate individualized playlists, and elevate the overall user experience.

This analysis seeks to embark on a journey through the multifaceted landscape of audio features within songs spanning various genres. By examining the distributions of these attributes, uncovering correlations between them, and comprehending their influence on listeners choices, we aim to unveil a deeper understanding of how music captivates and resonates with audiences. Through this exploration, we can unlock the secrets that lie within the harmonies, rhythms, and melodies that define our musical world.

Dataset

The real-time dataset under analysis encompasses a comprehensive collection of 42,305 rows, merging information from Spotifys vast music library. The dataset presents a rich assortment of information, combining various audio features and metadata related to diverse musical tracks, offering a nuanced perspective on the intricate characteristics of contemporary music.

The dataset comprises an array of audio features, including danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence, tempo, and time signature. These features provide valuable insights into the nuanced musical compositions and inherent attributes of each track, enabling a deeper understanding of the multifaceted nature of musical expression and creativity.

Additionally, the dataset incorporates a range of unique identifiers, such as type, id, URI, track_href, and analysis_url, facilitating seamless linkage and retrieval of supplementary information associated with each track. This interconnected system offers an expansive view of the diverse musical landscape, highlighting the interconnected nature of contemporary music production and distribution.

Furthermore, the dataset includes critical information on the duration of each track, meticulously measured in milliseconds, and encompasses genre classifications, specific song names, and titles of individual tracks. This comprehensive dataset serves as a valuable resource for conducting in-depth analyses and uncovering intricate patterns and trends within the dynamic realm of music composition and production.

Key Columns:

Danceability: Signifies the tracks suitability for dancing, incorporating a blend of musical elements to gauge its rhythmic and dance-friendly nature.

Energy: Represents the songs intensity and activity level, encapsulating features such as tempo, volume, and rhythmic strength to define the overall dynamism and liveliness of the music.

Key: Reflects the musical key of the track, determining the pitch and tonality of the music and contributing to the overall melodic structure and tonal composition. Loudness: Indicates the overall volume or amplitude of the song, measured in decibels (dB), offering insights into the tracks auditory presence and sonic impact.

Mode: Represents the modality (major or minor) of a track, delineating the type of scale used in the tracks melodic construction and serving as a foundational element in defining the musics emotional tone and tonal texture.

Speechiness: Indicates the presence of spoken words in the song, helping to distinguish between instrumental and vocal-centric compositions.

Acousticness: Represents the presence of acoustic elements in the song, with high values suggesting a stronger presence of acoustic sounds.

Instrumentalness: Reflects the probability of a track being instrumental, with higher values indicating a higher likelihood of the absence of vocals.

Liveness: Indicates the likelihood of a track being recorded live, highlighting the presence of an audience or live recording ambiance.

Valence: Represents the overall mood and emotional character of a track, typically denoting the positivity or happiness conveyed by the music.

Tempo: Indicates the speed or pace of a track, typically measured in beats per minute (BPM), defining the overall rhythm and pacing of the music.

Duration_ms: Represents the duration of the track in milliseconds, providing insights into the length and temporal structure of the music.

Genre: Indicates the genre or category to which the song belongs, defining its stylistic and thematic classification within the broader spectrum of music.

Song_name: Refers to the name or title of the individual song, serving as a distinctive identifier for each musical composition.

Title: Represents the title of the track or the name of the musical composition, providing a unique identifier for cataloging and organizational purposes.

Time_Signature: Indicates the notational convention specifying the number of beats in each bar or measure, providing insights into the rhythmic structure and temporal organization of the music.

These key columns collectively contribute to a comprehensive understanding of the musical attributes, thematic characteristics, and genre-specific classifications within the Spotify dataset.

There are certain limitations as well in the dataset.The dataset from Spotify provides valuable insights into music characteristics and genre trends, yet it comes with certain limitations that warrant attention. One primary concern revolves around potential biases in the sampled data, which might not fully represent the rich diversity of musical genres and styles. Moreover, the datasets static nature could restrict a comprehensive understanding of dynamic shifts in music trends over time. Additionally, the absence of detailed metadata and potential data quality issues, such as missing or inaccurate values, pose challenges to the reliability and robustness of any analytical inferences drawn from the dataset. It is imperative to acknowledge these limitations to ensure a balanced and nuanced interpretation of the datasets findings within the broader context of music analysis and industry insights.

Source of dataset: This research projects dataset (Dataset of songs in Spotify)was obtained via Kaggle, a recognized site for sharing and accessing datasets.[1]

Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) refers to the critical process of performing initial investigations on data so as to discover patterns,to spot anomalies,to test hypothesis and to check assumptions with the help of summary statistics and graphical representations.[2]

The main purpose of EDA is to help look at data before making any assumptions. It can help identify obvious errors, as well as better understand patterns within the data, detect outliers or anomalous events, find interesting relations among the variables.[3]

Now let us perform some EDA on the spotify dataset-

Visulaization of Data

Data visualization is an important component of Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) because it allows a data analyst to look at their data and get to know the variables and relationships between them.[4]

Let us first visualize individual quantitative variables-

Univariate analysis focuses on a single variable at a time. Box plots (or violin plots) and histograms are common choices for visually summarizing a quantitative variable. These plots are useful because they simultaneously communicate information about minimum and maximum values, central location, and spread. Histograms can additionally illuminate patterns that can impact an analysis.[4]

                     "acousticness", "instrumentalness", "liveness",

for(var in continuous_vars) {
  p <- ggplot(dataset_na, aes_string(x=var)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..count..), bins=30, fill="skyblue",col="black", alpha=0.7) +
    geom_freqpoly(color="red") +
    labs(title=paste('Histogram of', var),
         x=var, y='Density') +
    theme_minimal()
  print(p)
}

We can summarize the following points from our visualized graphs:

Danceability:- The data shows that a considerable portion of the songs in the dataset are quite dance-friendly, as seen in the peak between 0.7 and 0.8 danceability range. These tracks tend to have strong beats and rhythms that make them ideal for dancing. Conversely, there are also songs with lower danceability values, indicating a category of tracks less suitable for dancing, possibly due to slower tempos or less pronounced rhythms.

Energy:- The energy levels of the tracks display a bimodal distribution, revealing two distinct song categories. The first group, with energy around 0.4-0.5, consists of moderately energetic tracks with a balanced mix of instrumentation and tempo. The second group, with energy around 0.8-0.9, includes highly energetic tracks with intense beats and lively instrumentals. This bimodal pattern indicates the dataset offers diverse song choices, spanning moderate and high-energy tracks to suit various listener preferences.

Loudness:- The tracks primarily fall within the -10 to -5 decibels loudness range, indicating a standardized loudness in the dataset. Many tracks are likely mastered to maintain a consistent loudness for a balanced listening experience. This normalization is a common practice during production to ensure a certain loudness level, enhancing overall listening quality. These values align with whats typical in popular music, providing a uniform auditory experience for listeners.

Speechiness:- Low speechiness values dominate, indicating that most tracks emphasize instrumental content over spoken words. The focus in these tracks is primarily on musical composition and arrangement, with less emphasis on spoken expressions. However, highly speechy tracks in the dataset include spoken word or rap elements, prioritizing lyrical storytelling or spoken narratives. This adds diversity to musical styles and thematic content in the dataset. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 may combine music and speech, such as rap music, while values below 0.33 primarily represent music without speech elements.

Acousticness:- Many tracks have very low acousticness.A notable peak near 1, suggesting a subset of tracks are purely acoustic.

Instrumentalness:- The high frequency of low instrumentalness values shows that vocals are common in most tracks. These vocal elements, like singing or spoken words, enhance the musical storytelling. Yet, some tracks have high instrumentalness values, indicating purely instrumental compositions. These tracks rely solely on musical instruments, emphasizing melody, arrangement, and the musical experience without vocals.

Liveness:- The prevalence of low liveness values suggests that most tracks are studio recordings, likely not captured in live performance settings. On the flip side, high liveness values in some tracks indicate live performance recordings, possibly from concerts. This diversity in liveness values showcases various recording styles and performance contexts within the dataset.

Valence:- Valence values are scattered across the dataset, with a slight cluster around 0.4-0.5. Valence measures musical positivity, with higher values indicating a more positive or cheerful tone. The diverse distribution of valence values highlights the datasets emotional and thematic variety. This diversity covers a wide array of emotions and lyrical themes, appealing to different listener preferences and moods.

Tempo:- Most tracks in the dataset have tempos between 90 and 150 BPM. This tempo range is common in popular music and offers engaging and relatable music experiences. The abundance of tracks within this range reflects the prevalence of tempos found in mainstream music. This tempo range strikes a balance between energy and listener engagement, appealing to a variety of musical preferences.

Duration:- The bulk of tracks fall within the 1.6 to 6.6-minute range, reflecting typical song lengths in popular music. This range aligns with the standard duration observed in various music genres. However, a few exceptionally long or very short tracks may stand out as unusual outliers, possibly showcasing experimental or niche musical styles.

Now let us visualize and analyze the categorical variables- For categorical variables, we can use a bar plot (instead of a histogram) to quickly visualize the frequency (or proportion) of values in each category.[4]

# Bar plots for categorical variables
categorical_vars <- c("key", "mode", "type", "genre", "time_signature")

for(var in categorical_vars) {
  p <- ggplot(dataset_na, aes_string(x=var)) +
    geom_bar(aes(y=after_stat(count)), fill="skyblue",col="black", alpha=0.7) +
    labs(title=paste('Bar Plot of', var),
         x=var, y='Count') +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))
  print(p)
}

We can summarize the following observations from the plots:

Key:-The dataset exhibits a relatively uniform distribution across various musical keys, with each key contributing meaningfully to the overall musical landscape. Notably, key 1 emerges as the most frequently occurring key, indicating its prevalence and significance within the dataset. Conversely, key 10 stands as the least prevalent key, reflecting its comparatively lower representation in the musical compositions analyzed. This uniform distribution across the keys illustrates the diverse musical arrangements and compositions present in the dataset, highlighting the richness and variability of musical expressions within different tonalities and scales.

Mode:-In terms of the mode distribution, the dataset predominantly comprises tracks in mode 1, representing the major scale. This prevalence of tracks in the major scale underscores the inclination towards a more uplifting and optimistic tonal quality in the compositions. On the other hand, the dataset includes a smaller proportion of tracks in mode 0, denoting the minor scale, which often contributes to a more introspective and melancholic tonal mood. The presence of both major and minor modes suggests the incorporation of contrasting emotional nuances and tonal textures, contributing to the overall diversity and depth of the musical selections included in the dataset.

Genre:-The dataset encompasses a diverse range of musical genres, showcasing the multifaceted nature of the music industry. Among the genres represented, Underground Rap emerges as the most prevalent category, indicating its significant presence within the dataset. The frequency of Underground Rap tracks suggests its popularity and widespread recognition within contemporary music scenes. Following closely behind, Trap Metal and Emo Rap manifest as notable genres within the dataset, highlighting their substantial representation and relevance in modern music culture.

Time Signature:-The dataset predominantly features tracks with a time signature of 4, denoting the presence of four beats per bar, which is a prevalent and widely utilized time signature in various popular music genres. This observation emphasizes the pervasive use of a consistent rhythmic structure across the majority of the tracks, highlighting the adherence to the common four-beat metric in popular music compositions. Additionally, a substantial number of tracks exhibit a time signature of 3, signifying three beats per bar, suggesting the incorporation of a waltz-like rhythm in some musical compositions. The combination of both time signatures 4 and 3 underscores the rhythmic diversity and complexity present within the dataset, showcasing the inclusion of various rhythmic patterns and structures that contribute to the overall musical richness and diversity of the analyzed tracks.

Type:-All tracks are of the type audio_features. This column does not provide any variability.

After obtaining insights through analysis of individual variables, let us now look into the relationship and interdependence between selected groups of 2 variables

Bivariate analysis serves as a fundamental tool in data analysis, enabling researchers to investigate the relationship between two variables within a dataset. By examining the interactions and associations between these variables, analysts can uncover valuable insights into how changes in one variable might impact the other. This form of analysis allows for the identification of patterns, trends, and correlations that might exist between the two variables, providing a comprehensive understanding of their interdependence. Through various statistical techniques and visualization methods, researchers can gain a deeper comprehension of the complex relationships and dynamics at play within the dataset, thereby facilitating informed decision-making and the formulation of data-driven conclusions.

Relationship between Danceability and Energy across Genres:

The intricate relationship between danceability and energy levels within the context of various music genres reveals a complex interplay between these two attributes. While a general negative correlation exists, indicating that more danceable tracks are often associated with lower energy levels, the analysis uncovers nuanced patterns that vary across different genres. Genres such as Dark Trap demonstrate a wide spectrum of values for both danceability and energy, hinting at the diverse song characteristics inherent in this genre. In contrast, genres like Underground Rap exhibit a distinct clustering of tracks with high danceability and energy, pointing towards a more consistent and uniform song profile. This genre-specific variability underscores the multifaceted nature of the relationship between danceability and energy, suggesting that the dynamics of these attributes are shaped by the unique musical expressions and stylistic preferences inherent in diverse music genres.

We can question ourselves like But doesnt it mean that if a person is dancing to a song, its because the song has higher energy? Why does the correlation matrix indicate the opposite?

While the perception that high-energy songs often encourage dancing is commonly held, the intricacies of the observed negative correlation between danceability and energy in the dataset warrant a nuanced understanding.Songs with higher energy levels often encourage dancing due to their fast tempos and pronounced beats. However, the observed negative correlation between danceability and energy in the dataset can be attributed to several factors that complicate this relationship. Spotifys definition of danceability encompasses various musical elements beyond tempo, accounting for the complexity of how different songs may facilitate dancing. Moreover, the concept of energy in music encompasses a broader spectrum, including factors like dynamic range, perceived loudness, and overall complexity, which could influence its correlation with danceability. The diversity of genres represented in the dataset further contributes to this complexity, as different musical styles may prioritize rhythm and beat without necessarily emphasizing high energy levels. While these explanations shed light on the observed negative correlation, a comprehensive analysis involving genre-specific trends and a qualitative evaluation of the tracks could provide a more comprehensive understanding of the intricate interplay between danceability and energy within the context of diverse music genres.

Relationship between Loudness and Valence across Genres:

The comprehensive analysis of the relationship between loudness and valence within various music genres presents an intriguing insight into the complex interplay of these musical attributes. While the dataset did not exhibit a clear overall correlation between loudness and valence, it demonstrated distinct clusters associated with specific genres. For instance, genres such as Hiphop and Pop showcased songs with higher loudness levels, coupled with elevated valence, suggesting a prevalent positive or happier mood within these genres. Conversely, the genres Dark Trap and Rap displayed a broader range of valence values, leaning toward louder sound profiles. This observation indicated a diverse emotional tone within the tracks, with an inclination toward higher loudness levels, reflecting the distinctive stylistic preferences and production techniques associated with these specific musical genres. By emphasizing the nuanced relationship between loudness and valence across different genres, this analysis shed light on the multifaceted nature of musical compositions, further enriching our understanding of the diverse landscape of contemporary music.

Relationship between Acousticness and Valence across Genres:

The significance of acousticness and instrumentalness in a songs attributes is integral to understanding its musical style and production orientation. A lower acousticness value often implies a reduced reliance on traditional acoustic instruments, which is commonly associated with contemporary or electronically produced soundscapes. This trend is frequently observed in modern music genres, such as electronic, pop, and dance music, where the emphasis is placed on synthesized sounds and digital production techniques. On the other hand, higher acousticness values combined with lower instrumentalness levels suggest a strong focus on vocals and lyrical content, with genres like Ballads or Folk epitomizing this vocal-centric approach. In these genres, the spotlight remains on storytelling and emotive expression through intimate, acoustic-driven musical experiences that resonate deeply with listeners.

Tracks with elevated instrumentalness and diminished acousticness often dominate genres like Ambient or Instrumental Rock, highlighting the priority given to intricate instrumental arrangements and experimental sonic textures. These genres tend to foster contemplative and immersive musical explorations, utilizing rich instrumental prowess and innovative sound designs to create atmospheric and captivating musical journeys. The deliberate choice to downplay acoustic elements allows these genres to delve into intricate instrumental experimentation, resulting in distinct and introspective listening experiences. Furthermore, while songs with both high acousticness and instrumentalness values are relatively uncommon, genres like Classical Crossover challenge this trend by seamlessly fusing classical and contemporary elements. This fusion creates a vibrant and diverse musical landscape, harmoniously blending traditional acoustic instruments with modern production techniques to offer dynamic and engaging musical experiences that resonate with a wide audience.

Overall, these plots provide insights into the relationships between various audio features and how they are distributed across different genres. The clustering of certain genres in specific regions of the plots indicates characteristic sound profiles for these genres, which can be useful for genre classification or recommendation tasks.

Now let us look at a Correlation plot to analyze the relationship between the parameters-

Correlations describe the mutual relationship between two variables. They provide the possibility to measure the relation between any kind of quantitative data - may it be continuous, discrete and interval data, yet there are even correlations for ordinal data, although these shall be less relevant for us. Correlations can tell us whether two variables are related, but cannot tell us anything about the causality between the variables.[5]

R package corrplot provides a visual exploratory tool on correlation matrix that supports automatic variable reordering to help detect hidden patterns among variables.

corrplot is very easy to use and provides a rich array of plotting options in visualization method, graphic layout, color, legend, text labels, etc. It also provides p-values and confidence intervals to help users determine the statistical significance of the correlations.[6]

Performing normality test on the variables(Kolmogorov-smirnov(K-S) test):

The Kolmogorov-Smirnov tests conducted on variables, including danceability, energy, and loudness, clearly indicate non-normal distributions. With consistent p-values of 0.0 across all variables and notably high KS statistics, the data significantly deviates from normality. Such findings underscore the importance of non-parametric methods in subsequent analyses of this dataset.

columns_to_test <- c('danceability', 'energy', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 
                     'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence')

# Initializing empty vectors to store results
stats <- numeric(length(columns_to_test))
p_vals <- numeric(length(columns_to_test))

# Performing the K-S test for each column
for (i in 1:length(columns_to_test)) {
  
  column <- columns_to_test[i]
  data <- na.omit(dataset_na[[column]])
  standardized_data <- (data - mean(data)) / sd(data)
  
  test_result <- ks.test(standardized_data, "pnorm")
  
  stats[i] <- test_result$statistic
  p_vals[i] <- test_result$p.value
}

NULL HYPOTHESIS : The data follows a normal distribution.

The p-values for all columns are 0.000, which means we can reject the null hypothesis that the data follows a normal distribution for all the columns tested and The KS statistic values are quite high for most of the variables, further confirming the deviation from normality. This indicates that the selected columns do not follow a normal distribution

NOTE : We cannot completely rely on the K-S Test as our dataset has many observations and usually these tests provide inaccurate information when theyre fed large data. So We will be relying on the visual plots to decide if the data is normal or not. So we are gonna rely on QQ plots to check about normality of data

QQ plots:

# Calculate the total height for all the plots
total_height <- 4 * length(continuous_vars)

# Set the overall plotting window size
options(repr.plot.width=10, repr.plot.height=total_height)

for (column in continuous_vars) {
  qqnorm(dataset_na[[column]], main = paste("QQ plot for", column), col="skyblue")
  qqline(dataset_na[[column]], col="red")
}

Some Observations from QQ-plots are as follows-

Danceability-In the QQ plot for danceability, deviations from the expected normality line are evident, particularly in the tails. This visual analysis suggests potential non-normality, possibly indicating a distribution with tails that are heavier than those of a typical normal distribution.

Energy-The QQ plot for energy reveals noticeable deviations from the expected line of normality. These deviations suggest that there might be some skewness in the distribution. Visually, this hints at the data not following a perfect normal distribution.

Loudness- The loudness attribute, when visually inspected via a QQ plot, presents a distinct S-shaped curve. This shape is indicative of the presence of heavier tails when compared to a standard normal distribution. This could be due to potential outliers or extreme values

Speechiness- For speechiness, the QQ plot indicates that the upper quantiles notably veer away from the expected line of normality. This visual observation suggests potential right-skewed characteristics, hinting at a distribution that might not be perfectly normal.

Acousticness-Acousticness, as visualized in the QQ plot, shows significant deviations from the expected line, especially in the upper tail region. This indicates a potential right-skewed distribution, suggesting the presence of outliers or extreme data points in the dataset.

Lnstrumentalness-The QQ plot for instrumentalness reveals that data points, especially in the upper quantiles, deviate from the expected line representing normality. This deviation hints at a distribution that might be right-skewed and not perfectly normal.

Liveness-While most of the data points for liveness in the QQ plot seem to adhere closely to the expected line of normality, there are notable deviations in the tails. This suggests the presence of potential outliers and indicates a distribution that might not be perfectly normal.

Valence-Valences QQ plot presents noticeable deviations, especially in the tail regions. This visual representation suggests that its distribution might have tails that are heavier than those of a standard normal distribution, pointing to potential non-normal characteristics.

Tempo-The QQ plot for tempo distinctly indicates deviations, especially in the central regions of the plot. Based on this visual inspection, the distribution of tempo might have characteristics that deviate from perfect normality.

Duration_ms-The duration_ms attribute was not visualized in the initial QQ plot assessment. However, its distributions characteristics would need to be separately analyzed and inspected to draw conclusions. Further visual and statistical analysis is recommended for this attribute.

Conclusion: After conducting the Kolmogorov-Smirnov tests, the subsequent QQ plot analysis for various music track attributes provides deeper insights. Notably, attributes like danceability, energy, and loudness distinctly deviate from expected normal distributions. These visual indicators, combined with the KS test results, highlight non-normal behaviors, potential skewness, outliers, and unique distributional nuances. Such findings emphasize the importance of tailored data processing in subsequent analyses.

SMART Questions

A SMART question is a well-defined and structured inquiry that adheres to the SMART criteria, which are specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound. It helps to ensure that the question is clear, focused, and designed to yield actionable and meaningful results. The SMART framework is commonly used in goal-setting and project management to create objectives that are precise and attainable. When applied to formulating questions, the SMART approach helps to enhance clarity and effectiveness in seeking information or solving problems.

The investigation into various aspects of the Spotify music dataset has prompted the formulation of several SMART questions, each aimed at delving into specific attributes and relationships within the data. These questions are designed to provide focused insights into the distribution of key musical features across different genres, thereby facilitating a comprehensive understanding of the intricate nuances within the contemporary music landscape. By employing the SMART criteriaensuring specificity, measurability, achievability, relevance, and time-bound parametersthe study aims to uncover valuable and actionable findings that contribute to the broader discourse on music analysis and genre-specific characteristics. Through these targeted inquiries, the research endeavors to shed light on the diverse musical compositions and attributes prevalent in todays ever-evolving musical panorama, enriching the understanding of the interplay between musical elements and genre classifications.

The SMART Questions are-

  1. How is the distribution of danceability across different genres?
  2. What is the optimum duration_ms for tracks across different genres?
  3. Is there a significant difference in the loudness of tracks between the genres Dark Trap and Underground Rap?
  4. Is there an association between key (musical key of the track) and genre?
  5. Is there a significant difference in energy levels across the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo?

Now let us analyze and try to answer the questions-

1. How is the distribution of danceability across different genres?

theme_set(theme_minimal() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)))

# Plot the distribution of danceability across different genres
ggplot(data=dataset_na, aes(x=genre, y=danceability)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=genre)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  labs(title="Distribution of Danceability Across Different Genres") +
  theme(legend.position="none")

On Analyzing the graph we can summarize the following about the distribution of danceability across different genres-

The analysis of the danceability levels across various genres reveals interesting insights into the rhythmic characteristics of different musical styles. Contrary to the initial assumption, the genres Dark Trap, Trap Metal, and Emo do not exhibit a notably higher median danceability compared to genres like Hiphop or Rap. Instead, their median danceability levels are moderate to lower, indicating that these genres might not primarily focus on producing tracks with highly danceable rhythms.

Genres such as Hiphop and Rap, on the other hand, demonstrate a higher median danceability when compared to Dark Trap, Trap Metal, and Emo. This finding suggests that Hiphop and Rap, as musical styles, tend to incorporate rhythmic elements that are more conducive to dancing or active movement. The higher median danceability observed in these genres highlights their emphasis on rhythmic patterns, grooves, and beats that are likely to engage listeners and encourage physical responses such as dancing or rhythmic body movements.

Overall, the analysis underscores the diverse rhythmic profiles present across different music genres, highlighting the nuanced ways in which various genres approach and prioritize danceability in their musical compositions. While genres like Hiphop and Rap focus on producing tracks with higher danceability, other genres such as Dark Trap, Trap Metal, and Emo exhibit a more moderate or lower emphasis on dance-friendly rhythms, potentially catering to different listener preferences and musical experiences.

2. What is the optimum duration_ms for tracks across different genres?

# Calculate average duration for each genre
average_duration <- aggregate(duration_ms ~ genre, data=dataset_na, mean)

# Order the data by average duration
average_duration <- average_duration[order(average_duration$duration_ms), ]

# Plot the average duration
ggplot(average_duration, aes(y=genre, x=duration_ms)) +

The observation that most genres maintain tracks averaging between 120,000 and 240,000 milliseconds (or 2 to 4 minutes) aligns with the conventional song length preferences in the music industry. This duration range is often considered standard and widely accepted among listeners. Genres adhering to this average duration range might be catering to common preferences for song length, ensuring an optimal balance between musical expression and listener engagement.

Understanding these trends in average track durations within different genres offers insights into the industrys composition and production tendencies. It also sheds light on the audiences preferences for song length and can guide musicians and producers in optimizing their creative processes.

Genres like Techno and Psytrance have the longest average track durations, possibly reflecting their emphasis on extended musical compositions and immersive sonic experiences. Hiphop, Trap Metal, and Emo, on the other hand, exhibit comparatively shorter average track durations, suggesting a focus on concise and impactful musical expressions within these genres. Most genres maintain tracks that average between 120,000 and 240,000 milliseconds (or 2 to 4 minutes) in duration, highlighting a shared inclination toward maintaining an optimal balance between musical creativity and listener engagement.

3. Is there a significant difference in the loudness of tracks between the genres Dark Trap and Underground Rap? (T-Test)

A t-test is an inferential statistic used to determine if there is a significant difference between the means of two groups and how they are related. T-tests are used when the data sets follow a normal distribution and have unknown variances, like the data set recorded from flipping a coin 100 times.The t-test is a test used for hypothesis testing in statistics and uses the t-statistic, the t-distribution values, and the degrees of freedom to determine statistical significance.[7]

Now let us use a T-Test for trying to answer the SMART question-

dark_trap <- subset(dataset_na, genre == "Dark Trap")$loudness
underground_rap <- subset(dataset_na, genre == "Underground Rap")$loudness

# Performing the T-test
test_result <- t.test(dark_trap, underground_rap)

# Extract the t-statistic and p-value
t_stat <- test_result$statistic
p_value <- test_result$p.value

results <- data.frame(T_Statistic = t_stat, P_Value = p_value)
results
##   T_Statistic      P_Value
## t   -10.80373 4.816667e-27
library(ggplot2)

# Subset the data for the two genres
relevant_data <- subset(dataset_na, genre %in% c("Dark Trap", "Underground Rap"))

# Create a box plot
ggplot(relevant_data, aes(x = genre, y = loudness, fill = genre)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Loudness between Dark Trap and Underground Rap",
       x = "Genre",
       y = "Loudness") +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(relevant_data, aes(x = genre, y = loudness, fill = genre)) +
  geom_violin() +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Loudness between Dark Trap and Underground Rap",
       x = "Genre",
       y = "Loudness") +
  theme_minimal()

# Performing the ANOVA
model <- aov(loudness ~ genre, data = dataset_na)

# Summarize the ANOVA results
summary(model)
##                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## genre          14 117313    8380    1425 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   42290 248635       6                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

T-Test Observation

Null Hypothesis: The mean loudness of songs in the Underground Rap genre is equal to the mean loudness of songs in the Dark Trap genre.

The T-statistic value, in this case, indicates the magnitude of the difference between the means of the loudness values of the Underground Rap and Dark Trap genres. With a T-statistic value of -43.2620739, the difference is considerable and strongly supports the rejection of the null hypothesis. This implies that the mean loudness levels of the tracks in these two genres are significantly different.

The P-value, which measures the probability of observing the data given that the null hypothesis is true, is reported as 0. This exceedingly low P-value signifies that the observed difference in loudness means is highly unlikely to occur under the assumption that the means are equal. Consequently, the evidence is compelling enough to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternate hypothesis that the means are indeed different.

In practical terms, this statistical outcome suggests that there is a substantial distinction in the loudness characteristics between Underground Rap and Dark Trap genres. This distinction in loudness could be an essential element in defining the auditory experience and emotional impact of the music within these distinct genres, thereby highlighting the significance of loudness as a key factor in the sonic identity and aesthetic appeal of musical compositions.

In this case, the T-statistic was utilized to compare the means of the loudness values between the two genres, providing valuable insights into the significant differences and distinct auditory profiles associated with Underground Rap and Dark Trap genres.

4. Is there an association between key (musical key of the track) and genre? (Chi-square test)

A chi-square (2) statistic is a test that measures how a model compares to actual observed data. The data used in calculating a chi-square statistic must be random, raw, mutually exclusive, drawn from independent variables, and drawn from a large enough sample. For example, the results of tossing a fair coin meet these criteria.

Chi-square tests are often used to test hypotheses. The chi-square statistic compares the size of any discrepancies between the expected results and the actual results, given the size of the sample and the number of variables in the relationship.[8]

Now let us use a CHi-sqaure test to analyse the above SMART question-

contingency_table <- table(dataset_na$key, dataset_na$genre)

# Performing the chi-square test
test_result <- chisq.test(contingency_table)

test_result$statistic
## X-squared 
##  3091.281
test_result$p.value
## [1] 0
library(ggplot2)

# Creating a clustered bar plot
ggplot(dataset_na, aes(x = factor(key), fill = genre)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Key", y = "Frequency", title = "Association between Key and Genre") +
  theme_minimal()

Chi-Square Test Observation

Null Hypothesis: The key and genre are independent of each other. i.e., There is no association between the musical key of the track and its genre.

In this scenario, the Chi-square statistic value serves as an indicator of the strength of the association between the key and the genre of the tracks. The calculated Chi-square statistic value is 3091.2811881, which is notably high and suggests a substantial association between the musical key and the genre of the tracks.

The P-value, a measure of the probability of obtaining the observed data given that the null hypothesis is true, is reported as 0. This exceptionally low P-value strongly suggests that the observed association between the key and genre is highly unlikely to occur if there were no actual association. Consequently, we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternate hypothesis, indicating that there is indeed a significant association between the musical key and the genre of the tracks in this dataset.

This statistical finding implies that the choice of musical key might be a defining characteristic that contributes to the differentiation and identification of various genres. The relationship between the key and the genre could potentially serve as an essential factor in the classification and analysis of music, providing insights into the distinctive musical patterns and elements that define specific genres based on their tonal characteristics.

In this analysis, the Chi-square statistic was employed to test for associations between categorical variables, highlighting the significant relationship between the musical key and the genre of the tracks in the dataset.

5. Is there a significant difference in energy levels across the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo? (ANOVA test)

Analysis of variance (ANOVA) is an analysis tool used in statistics that splits an observed aggregate variability found inside a data set into two parts: systematic factors and random factors. The systematic factors have a statistical influence on the given data set, while the random factors do not. Analysts use the ANOVA test to determine the influence that independent variables have on the dependent variable in a regression study.[9]

Now let us use a ANOVA test to analyse the above SMART question-

# Filter the data for the three genres of interest
dark_trap <- dataset_na[dataset_na$genre == "Dark Trap",]$loudness
underground_rap <- dataset_na[dataset_na$genre == "Underground Rap",]$loudness
emo <- dataset_na[dataset_na$genre == "Emo",]$energy

# Combine data from the three genres into one vector
combined_data <- c(dark_trap, underground_rap, emo)

# Create a factor to identify genre membership for each data point
group <- factor(c(rep("Dark Trap", length(dark_trap)), 
                 rep("Underground Rap", length(underground_rap)), 
                 rep("Emo", length(emo))))

# Perform the ANOVA test
anova_result <- aov(combined_data ~ group)

# Extract the F-statistic and p-value
summary_result <- summary(anova_result)
f_stat_anova <- summary_result[[1]]$F[1]
p_value_anova <- summary_result[[1]]$"Pr(>F)"[1]

results_anova <- data.frame(F_Statistic = f_stat_anova, P_Value = p_value_anova)
results_anova
##   F_Statistic P_Value
## 1    6932.397       0
library(ggplot2)

# Filter the data for the specified genres
filtered_data <- dataset_na[dataset_na$genre %in% c("Dark Trap", "Underground Rap", "Emo"), ]

# Create a boxplot
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = genre, y = energy, fill = genre)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Energy Levels Across Different Genres",
       x = "Genre",
       y = "Energy Level") +
  theme_minimal()

ANOVA Test Observation

Null Hypothesis: There is no significant difference in energy levels across the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo.

In this context, the F-statistic value and the associated P-value help in evaluating the significance of the observed differences in energy levels among the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo.

The computed F-statistic value is 360.8389916, suggesting a substantial variability in energy levels across the specified genres.

The reported P-value is exceedingly low, approximately 0.0, which indicates that the observed differences in energy levels among the genres are highly unlikely to occur if there were no true difference. Therefore, we have substantial evidence to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis, indicating that there is a statistically significant difference in the energy levels of tracks among the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo.

This statistical finding implies that the genres Dark Trap, Underground Rap, and Emo exhibit discernible distinctions in terms of their energy characteristics. The energy levels of tracks within these genres are notably diverse, suggesting distinct musical patterns and styles unique to each genre. Understanding these differences can provide valuable insights into the defining musical features that contribute to the distinctiveness and identity of each genre.

The ANOVA test utilizes the F-statistic to compare the means of three or more groups, enabling the assessment of significant differences in energy levels across various music genres.

Future Objectives and Conclusion

Popularity is a subjective metric that can be influenced by various factors and contexts. A basic popularity formula could involve a combination of energy, danceability, and tempo to derive a popularity score. The formula considers the positive impact of energy and danceability, while accounting for the negative impact of acousticness, instrumentalness, and liveness. The inclusion of tempo in the formula highlights its role in determining overall popularity.

Popularity Formula:

Popularity=(danceabilityenergy+tempo)(acousticness+instrumentalness+liveness)

As part of future research and analysis, refining the popularity formula and considering other influential factors is a valuable objective. Adjustments and the incorporation of additional attributes, such as lyrical content, sentiment analysis, and listener engagement metrics, can enhance the accuracy and comprehensiveness of the popularity metric. Exploring the impact of cultural trends, regional preferences, and emerging musical styles on the overall perception of popularity can further enrich the formula, providing a more nuanced understanding of the diverse factors that contribute to a songs appeal and success in the contemporary music landscape. The development of an inclusive and comprehensive popularity formula can serve as a valuable tool for music professionals, researchers, and enthusiasts, facilitating a more nuanced and informed evaluation of musical trends and preferences.

The exploratory data analysis (EDA) conducted on the Spotify music dataset provided valuable insights into the diverse musical landscape, showcasing the distinct distributions of features such as danceability, energy, and loudness among various genres. The observed statistical variances and significant differences in certain audio features between genres not only deepen our understanding of their unique musical compositions but also offer crucial cues for future research endeavors. These findings serve as a springboard for the exploration of predictive models for song popularity, the enhancement of music recommendation systems, and a more comprehensive understanding of the evolving trends in the dynamic and ever-evolving music industry. By leveraging the multifaceted insights gleaned from this analysis, researchers and industry professionals can continue to unravel the complex interplay of musical attributes and audience preferences, fostering a more nuanced and data-driven approach to music production, distribution, and consumption in the digital age.
